    "enDesc": "Rabbi Chaim Vital, a prominent Safed kabbalist in the 16th-17th centuries, is best known for recording and editing the teachings of the Arizal (Rabbi Isaac Luria, considered a founder of modern kabbalah). Chaim Vital’s son, Rabbi Shmuel Vital, organized a collection of his father’s writings into eight “gates,” each of which “opens” up a particular topic. The seventh of these is Sha’ar Ruach HaKodesh (Gate of Divine Inspiration), which delves into practical application of Lurianic kabbalah as a meditative discipline. \n",
